        "#### Question #4\n",
        "\n",
        "Why is it useful to keep <code>synthesizer_name</code>,\n",
        "<code>synthetic_reference</code>, and review status as metadata instead of\n",
        "discarding them after upload?\n",
        "\n",
        "##### Answer\n",
        "\n",
        "Keeping synthesizer_name, synthetic_reference, and review_status as metadata makes the dataset auditable, diagnosable, and maintainable after it has been uploaded.\n",
        "\n",
        "1. synthesizer_name\n",
        "\n",
        "This identifies which query type generated the example (single-hop, multi-hop specific, multi-hop abstract). This immediately shows where the RAG system needs improvement.\n",
        "\n",
        "Why useful:\n",
        "\n",
        "Analyze evaluation results by question type.\n",
        "Identify whether failures are caused by retrieval, multi-hop reasoning, or abstract reasoning.\n",
        "Compare retriever changes on different categories of questions.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "2. synthetic_reference\n",
        "\n",
        "This indicates that the reference answer was generated by RAGAS rather than written by a human.\n",
        "\n",
        "Why useful:\n",
        "\n",
        "Distinguishes synthetic ground truth from human-authored ground truth.\n",
        "Helps interpret evaluation scores appropriately.\n",
        "Makes it easier to replace synthetic references with human-curated ones later.\n",
        "Supports dataset governance and provenance tracking.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "3. review_status\n",
        "\n",
        "This records whether a human reviewed the example.\n",
        "\n",
        "Why useful:\n",
        "\n",
        "Provides an audit trail showing dataset quality control.\n",
        "Lets you filter out unreviewed examples.\n",
        "Helps teams understand which examples are trusted.\n",
        "Supports reproducibility and compliance processes."
      ]
    },
