        "#### Question #6\n",
        "\n",
        "Why is changing one variable at a time useful? If correctness improves while\n",
        "retrieval relevance falls, what might the larger value of <code>k</code> be doing?\n",
        "\n",
        "##### Answer\n",
        "\n",
        "Changing one variable at a time is a core experimental principle because it lets you identify which change caused the observed effect\n",
        "\n",
        "If you change several things simultaneously:\n",
        "\n",
        "Chunk Size: 500 -> 1000\n",
        "k: 3 -> 8\n",
        "Embedding Model: Model A -> Model B\n",
        "\n",
        "and correctness improves from 0.75 to 0.88, you don't know:\n",
        "\n",
        "Was it the larger chunks?\n",
        "Was it the higher k?\n",
        "Was it the new embedding model?\n",
        "Was it some combination?\n",
        "\n",
        "That's called a confounded experiment.\n",
        "\n",
        "By changing only:\n",
        "\n",
        "k: 3 -> 6\n",
        "\n",
        "while keeping everything else fixed, you can confidently attribute any difference to the retrieval depth."
      ]
    },
